{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}} '''James Albert Beck''' (August 11, 1916 – May 3, 1956) was an [[United States|American]] country music talent agent, record promoter, recording studio owner, A&R engineer, record producer, and music publisher from [[Dallas, Texas]]. Born in [[Marshall, Texas]], Beck is credited with discovering and, in 1950, being the first to record [[Lefty Frizzell]]. He is also credited for introducing Frizzell and [[Ray Price (musician)|Ray Price]] to Frank Jones (1926–2005) of [[Columbia Records]], which led to their first major recording contracts. [[Marty Robbins]] recorded his first hit — "[[I'll Go on Alone]]" — at Beck's studio. Beck's studio also recorded a few hits by [[Carl Smith (country musician)|Carl Smith]] at his studio. Record labels and producers who recorded at Jim Beck Studios included [[Decca Records|Decca]] (via [[Paul Cohen (record producer)|Paul Cohen]]), [[Bullet Records|Bullet]], [[King Records (United States)|King]], [[Imperial Records|Imperial]], and [[Columbia Records]].<ref name="Western">"Ray Price," by [[Don Cusic]], ''[[The Western Way]]'' (magazine), Vol. 20, Issue 2, pg. 18 (Spring 2010) {{OCLC|49503705}}</ref><ref name="Interviews">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=1R1TiXZH4moC&pg=PA147&lpg=PA147&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false Voices of the Country: Interviews With Classic Country Performers,]'' Michael Streissguth, [[Routledge]] pg. 147 (2004) {{OCLC|53375146}}</ref> Between 1954 and 1956, [[Frankie Miller (country musician)|Frankie Miller]] recorded a series of singles for [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] at Beck's studio.<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=3Jorozp1yp4C&pg=PA131&lpg=PA131&dq Country Music: The Rough Guide,]'' by Kurt Wolff & Orla Duane, [[Rough Guides]], pg 131 (2000) {{OCLC|43718335}}</ref>
== Jim Beck Studio == Beck built his second studio — the "Jim Beck Studio" — in 1950 at 1101 Ross Avenue in Dallas.<ref>''Country: The Music and The Musicians — From the Beginnings to the '90s,'' [[Country Music Foundation]], pg. 118 (1994) {{OCLC|31483981}}</ref><ref name="Roots">[http://bestocm.com/Jim_Beck.html "The Professional Work of Jim Beck,"] Roots of Country Music — ''The Internet Encyclopedia of Original Country Music'' (publisher) (retrieved May 1, 2013)</ref> His first studio had been on Main Street in Dallas.<ref>"The Jim Beck Dallas Studio," ''The Journal of Country Music'', [[Country Music Foundation]], Vol. 11, Issue 1, pg. 1923 (1986) {{ISSN|0092-0517}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CE8xiT3pV6QC&pg=PT137&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false "Jim Beck," by Martin Donell Kohout, from ''The Handbook of Texas Music, Second Edition]'' edited by Laurie E. Jasinski, [[Texas State Historical Association]] (2012) {{OCLC|768792836}}</ref><ref>[http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2000-09-01/78455/ "For the Good Times: Country and Pop, 'The Same Thing',"] by David Cantwell, ''[[Austin Chronicle]],'' September 1, 2000</ref><ref>[http://www.well.com/conf/inkwell.vue/topics/329/Joe-Nick-Patoski-Willie-Nelson-a-page01.html "Inkwell: Authors and Artists, Topic 329: Joe Nick Patoski: Willie Nelson, an Epic Life,"] ''[[The WELL]], (various posts)'' (2008)</ref><ref name="Petty">[http://www.songwriter.co.uk/page53.html "ISA Norman Petty Interview,"] by Jim Liddane, [[Limerick]], Ireland: International Songwriters Association</ref><ref>[[Liner notes]] to [[Merle Haggard|Merle Haggard's]], ''[[Roots Volume I]],'' by Norm Stephens</ref> [[Norman Petty]], who later built and ran his own recording studio, worked as a part-time recording engineer at the Jim Beck Studio.<ref name="Petty" />
