{{hatnote|"Pelagia" redirects here. For another Pelagia of Antioch, see [[Pelagia the Virgin]]. For other uses, see [[Pelagia (disambiguation)]].}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox saint |name = Saint Pelagia <!--birth_date = 290? |death_date = 305 Removed ref History section, and that Nonnus was late 4th century --> |feast_day = {{unbulleted list | 8 October (Roman Catholic){{sfnp|Kirsch|1911}} | 8 October OS (Eastern Orthodox){{sfnp|Kirsch|1911}} | 8 October (Syriac Orthodox Church)<ref>Hugo Hoever, S.O.Cist., Ph.D., "Lives of the Saints", New York: Catholic Book Publishing Co., 1989</ref>}}{{dubious|Page and quote, please. It's not available online.|date=July 2018}} |venerated_in = {{unbulleted list | [[Roman Catholic Church]] | [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] | [[Syriac Orthodox Church]]}} |image = Saint pelagia.jpg |caption = Margarita among her courtesans, as [[Saint Nonnus]] prays for her (14th-century MS) |birth_place= |death_place= |titles= |beatified_date= |beatified_place= |beatified_by= |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |patronage= |major_shrine= |suppressed_date= |issues= }} '''Pelagia''' ({{lang-grc-gre|Πελαγία}}), distinguished as '''Pelagia of Antioch''', '''Pelagia the Penitent''', and '''Pelagia the Harlot''', was a [[Christianity|Christian]] [[Christian saint|saint]] and [[hermetism|hermit]] in the 4th or 5th century. Her [[feast day]] was celebrated on 8 October, originally in common with Saints [[Pelagia the Virgin]] and [[Pelagia of Tarsus]].<ref>Greek [[Synaxarion]].</ref>{{sfnp|Kirsch|1911}}{{refn|group=n|The [[Roman Martyrology]] eventually distinguished the dates of the other Pelagias, removing them to other months.{{sfnp|Kirsch|1911}}}}
==Legend== Pelagia's [[hagiography]], attributed to James{{sfnp|Coon|1997|p=[https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=w_1-t_K2ZuMC&pg=PA78 78]}}{{sfn|James the Deacon}} or Jacob{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=85}}{{sfn|James the Deacon}} ({{lang-la|Jacobus}}), [[deacon]] of the church of [[Heliopolis (Syria)|Heliopolis]] (modern [[Baalbek]]),{{sfnp|Bunson & al.|2003}} states that '''Margarita''' was the "foremost actress" and a prominent [[prostitution in ancient Rome|harlot]] in [[Antioch]].{{sfn|James the Deacon}} During one of the [[Synods of Antioch|city's church councils]], she passed by on a donkey surrounded by her entourage and a "worldly crowd".{{sfn|James the Deacon}} Perfumed and "immodestly" bareheaded, the outlines of her body were "clearly visible" beneath her [[gold cloth]], [[pearl]]s, and precious stones, which ran from her bare shoulders to her feet.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} Most of the fathers were shamed into looking away, but the bishop [[Saint Nonnus|Nonnus]] stared openly and confessed himself "delighted".{{sfn|James the Deacon}} Mocking his fellows, he condemned both them and himself for taking less care of their [[soul]]s than she had of her body.{{sfn|James the Deacon}}
She appeared at his next [[Sunday service|Sunday]] [[sermon]] and Nonnus's sermon on [[hell]]{{sfn|James the Deacon}} and the goodness of [[Christian Heaven|paradise]]{{sfn|James the Deacon}} prompted her to [[repentance|repent]]. She had two of her [[Roman slavery|slaves]] trail Nonnus to his residence and then wrote him on [[wax tablet]]s, calling herself "sinful" and a "servant of the [[devil]]" but seeking mercy from God, who "came down to earth not for the sake of the righteous but to save sinners".{{sfn|James the Deacon}} Nonnus replied to the anonymous request that God knew her and her past and that he would receive her, but only in the presence of the other bishops.{{sfn|James the Deacon}}
She went to the [[basilica]] of [[Julian of Antioch|Saint Julian]] to see them; when Nonnus demanded surety that she would not return to her former life, she fell to the ground and threatened that if she were refused admission to the Church, all her future sins would be held against him at his judgment.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} The archbishop was informed and sent the [[deaconess]] Romana to clothe her in the [[baptismal gown]].{{sfn|James the Deacon}} Nonnus took her confession and baptized "Margarita" under her birth name Pelagia, with Romana serving as her [[godparent|godmother]].{{sfn|James the Deacon}} The [[devil]] shortly afterward arrived to complain, but was driven off when Pelagia made the [[Sign of the Cross]] and breathed upon him.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} He returned the next night to renew his complaints and was driven off the same way.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} On the third day, Pelagia directed her slave [[steward (office)|steward]] to inventory her possessions. She then turned them over to Nonnus, who disbursed them to the widows, orphans, and poor of the city.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} She further [[manumission|freed her slaves]], male and female, "taking their golden [[torc]]s off with her own hands".{{sfn|James the Deacon}} She then began living with Romana.{{sfn|James the Deacon}}
The night before it came time to remove her baptismal gown, she stole out in the dark wearing one of Nonnus's [[Chiton (costume)|chiton]]s. She headed for [[Jerusalem]], where she built a [[cell (monk)|cell]] on the [[Mount of Olives]].{{sfn|James the Deacon}} She lived there for three or four years, disguising herself as a male [[hermit|recluse]] and [[eunuch]] under the name '''Pelagi<u>us</u>'''.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} She then died, apparently as a result of extreme [[asceticism]], which had emaciated her to the point she could no longer be recognized.{{sfn|James the Deacon}} Upon the discovery that the renowned monk had been a woman, the "holy fathers" tried to keep it a secret, but the gossip spread and her relics drew pilgrims from as far off as [[Jericho]] and the [[Jordan River|Jordan valley]].{{sfn|James the Deacon}}
The story appeared in the ''[[Menaea Graeca|Greek Menaea]]''.{{sfnp|Butler|1866}} It significantly omits dates and (on eight occasions) the name of the archbishop under whom Nonnus served.{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=87}}{{refn|group=n|One Greek account<ref>BHG 1479g.</ref> refers to the archbishop as [[Flavianus I of Antioch|Flavianus]] ({{abbr|r.|served}}&nbsp;381–404), although [[Alan Cameron (classical scholar)|Cameron]] dismisses its testimony.{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=88}}}}
==History== The [[Pelagia the Virgin|historical St&nbsp;Pelagia]], mentioned by [[St&nbsp;Ambrose]]<ref>[[Ambrose]], [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf210.iv.vii.iv.vii.html ''De Virg.'', III, 7, 33].</ref><ref>[[Ambrose]], ''Ep.'' xxxvii. ''ad Simplic.''</ref> and in two sermons by [[John Chrysostom]],<ref name=chrys>[[Chrysostom]], [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf110.iii.LXIV.html ''Hom. in Matth.'' lxvii.] {{la icon}}</ref> was an [[Antioch]]ene [[holy virgin|virgin]] who [[Christian martyrdom|committed suicide]] to avoid being forced to offer [[ancient Roman religion|pagan]] [[sacrifice]] during the [[Diocletianic Persecution]]. [[Marina the Monk|Saint Marina]], the Latin equivalent of "Pelagia", was another bride who became a transvestite monk, in her case to escape an unwanted marriage.{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=87}}{{refn|group=n|A third St&nbsp;Pelagia of Antioch was [[Margaret the Virgin|Saint Margaret]], whose name derives from its earlier form "Margarita".}} Aspects of their stories were apparently combined with [[New Testament apocrypha|apocrypha]]l accounts of [[Mary Magdalene]],{{sfnp|Coon|1997|p=[https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=w_1-t_K2ZuMC&pg=PA77 77–78]}} [[Bible|Biblical]] accounts of [[Solomon]] and the [[Queen of Sheba]] and of [[Jesus]] and various women in the [[New Testament]],{{sfnp|Coon|1997|pp=[https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=w_1-t_K2ZuMC&pg=PA80 80–82]}} and even with [[Greek myth]]s regarding [[Aphrodite]]{{sfnp|Usener|1879}}{{refn|group=n|[[Johann Peter Kirsch|Kirsch]],{{sfnp|Kirsch|1911}} however, considers [[Hermann Usener|Usener]]'s arguments associating the saints Pelagia with the pagan Aphrodite{{sfnp|Usener|1879}} to have been "completely disproved" by Delehaye.{{who|date=September 2015}}{{where?|date=September 2015}}{{why?|date=September 2015}}}} to create the story of the harlot Pelagia. [[John Chrysostom|Chrysostom]]'s {{circa|lk=no|390}} sermon also mentions an anonymous (but apparently famous) actress and prostitute "from a wicked city in [[Phoenice]]" (possibly [[Baalbek#History|Heliopolis]]) who seduced "the empress's brother" but converted "in our own day".{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=86–87}} [[Constantius II]]'s wife [[Eusebia (empress)|Eusebia]] had two brothers, [[Eusebius]] and [[Hypatius (consul 359)|Hypatius]], joint [[Roman consul|consuls]] in 359, who both lived for many years in Antioch.{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=87–88}} In his account, attempts were made to lure her back to her former life by the Roman prefect and some of his soldiers,<ref name=chrys/> a role played by Satan in the hagiography.{{sfnp|Cameron|2016|p=86}} The mention of a meeting of the Syrian bishops is unhelpful for dating, as more than thirty [[Synods of Antioch]] were conducted in late antiquity.
==See also== * Saints [[Pelagia the Virgin]] and [[Pelagia of Tarsus]], celebrated on the same day * Saints [[Margaret the Virgin]] and [[Marina the Monk]], both of whom are sometimes confused or conflated with Pelagia * [[Chapel of the Ascension, Jerusalem#The ''zawiya'' of Rabi'a al-'Adawiyya|The Jerusalem tomb]] venerated since the Byzantine times as Pelagia's
