In [[forensics|forensic investigation]], the '''time of occurrence''' of an event (such as time of death, time of incident) is one of the most important things to determine accurately as soon as possible. Sometimes this can only be estimated.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cienciaforense.com/pages/entomology/overview.htm#Estim|title = Forensic Entomology Overview}}</ref> Some indicators that investigators use are [[rigor mortis]], [[livor mortis]], [[algor mortis]], clouding of the [[cornea]]s, state of [[decomposition]], presence/absence of purged [[Bodily fluid|fluids]] and level of tissue [[desiccation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dplylemd.com/Articles/timelydeath.html|title=Timely Death|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515030306/http://www.dplylemd.com/Articles/timelydeath.html|archivedate=2007-05-15|df=}}</ref>

Pathologists can assume a time of death via analysing [[Carrion insects#Necrophagous species|necrophagous diptera]]. The odour from decaying flesh attracts different species as the stages of decomposition progress.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.inkling.com/read/fundamentals-of-forensic-science-houck-siegel-2nd/chapter-9/calculating-a-pmi|title = Fundamentals of Forensic Science|accessdate = September 11, 2013}}</ref>

